# Plan: Add Pagination to GET /users Endpoint

## Context
The `GET /users` endpoint in `src/routes.ts` currently returns the raw `users` array (all 15 users at once). The tests in `tests/routes.test.ts` already expect paginated responses with `{ data, pagination }` shape, so all 4 pagination tests are currently failing. The `GET /users/:id` endpoint and its 2 tests are unrelated and must remain passing.

## File to Modify
- **`src/routes.ts`** (lines 7–9) — the only file that needs changes

No new files are needed. No changes to `types.ts`, `data.ts`, `app.ts`, or tests.

## Implementation Steps

### Step 1: Parse query parameters (line 8 area)
Inside the `GET /users` handler, extract `page` and `limit` from `req.query`, parsing them as integers with defaults:
```ts
const page = parseInt(req.query.page as string, 10) || 1;
const limit = parseInt(req.query.limit as string, 10) || 10;
```

### Step 2: Compute pagination metadata
```ts
const total = users.length;                    // 15
const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);   // e.g. 2 when limit=10
```

### Step 3: Slice the data array
```ts
const start = (page - 1) * limit;
const data = users.slice(start, start + limit);
```
- When `page` is out of range (e.g. 100), `start` exceeds array length, so `slice` naturally returns `[]` — no special-case needed.

### Step 4: Return the paginated response
```ts
res.json({
  data,
  pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages },
});
```

### Summary of the edit
Replace lines 7–9 of `src/routes.ts`:
```ts
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  res.json(users);
});
```
with:
```ts
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page = parseInt(req.query.page as string, 10) || 1;
  const limit = parseInt(req.query.limit as string, 10) || 10;
  const total = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const start = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data = users.slice(start, start + limit);

  res.json({
    data,
    pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages },
  });
});
```

## Verification
Run the full test suite:
```
npm test
```
All 6 tests should pass (4 pagination + 2 user-by-id).

